There's a simple motive for Pence that Maggie missed: he knows the Russians are trying to influence Trump and he's trying to be a voice of reason. With the firing of Flynn and hiring of McMaster, it looks like that's exactly what he's been doing (see http://www.cnn.com/2017/02/20/politics/mike-pence-michael-flynn-comments/, http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/trump-names-lt-gen-hr-mcmaster-national-security/story?id=45617774, and http://wtop.com/dc/2017/02/trump-pick-as-security-adviser-is-independent-minded/). Instead, Haberman insists that Trump, Bannon and Kushner were "eager to find an excuse" to oust Flynn, somehow missed the dire warning from Yates, and waited 18 days and several embarrassing media reports later to finally fire him while Pence "gave them cover."

There are enough anomalies with Haberman's reporting to say with fair confidence, for the author at least, that she's one of the Russian propagandists. Corroborating this, access to Trump is decided by close Trump advisor Hope Hicks, who appears to favor Haberman:


