The Constitutionality of Trump's travel-ban is an important part of what looks like the strongest case for Trump's impeachment (abuse of power potential obstruction of justice; see https://pastebin.com/YrPgkGCR), and gerrymandering is a major roadblock for American voters who want to peacefully remove Congressmen that refuse to impeach Trump.

This illustrates another important point about Russian influence operations--it's not just planting ideas that benefit the Kremlin in people's heads (e.g. "annexing Poland is justified"), a lot of it is changing people's values in ways that make it easier for Russian agents to attack them or or easier to coax the people into attacking themselves. It's easier to place agents of influence among journalists who don't value honesty, easier to install spies in a Government that values winning partisan fights over the welfare of the country, and it's easier to get away with political influence operations in a country that allows super-PACs to do the same.

This is why its so important for the American people to fight back--the more we let them know that in America, a media that tells the truth is more important than a media that tells you what you want to hear, country comes above party, and democracy is for the people and not the highest bidder, the less these agents of influence can get away with. Defense of our values is defense of our country.

In the long term, this is what we've been doing, and we've been winning. In the 60's, the KGB thought they could use terrorist attacks and propaganda to spark a race war in America (https://medium.com/@bb06/ideological-subversion-and-racism-f3d09421cf78t); you'd be hard-pressed to find someone who thinks a plot like that could ever work today.

In the short term, its probably a good idea to figure out what Russians intend to do with Trump. Intent is hard to prove, but we can do our best to guess.

